data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new **span overload resolution** rules. When you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>`-based methods, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches ensure the expression tree binds to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is representable in expression trees. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` instead.
